<FlowDocument xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
              xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
              Foreground="#E0E0E0"
              Background="#1E1F22"
              FontFamily="Segoe UI"
              FontSize="14"
              PagePadding="32,24,32,24">

    <Paragraph FontSize="28" FontWeight="Bold" Foreground="#FFD700" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Create Traps Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Foreground="#A0A0A0" FontSize="13" Margin="0,0,0,16">
        Creates Steam Jet traps that can damage the player or NPCs, animate in timed on/off patterns, and be controlled through mission logic.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,0,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,4,0,4">
        What the Traps Event Point Does
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Traps</Bold> Event Point is used to create trap-style hazards in a mission.
        Currently, the available trap type is <Bold>Steam Jet</Bold>. This creates a jet of steam
        that comes out of pipes or vents and can harm the player or NPCs on the map.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        Steam traps are often used cosmetically to make industrial areas, sewers, warehouses,
        factories, or machinery rooms feel more alive. They can also be used as real hazards,
        obstacles, timing challenges, or item blockers.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_overview.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Critical requirement:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Steam Jet traps only work correctly when Listening Mode is set to Active While.
                    If the trap does not appear or does not animate correctly, check this setting first.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Adding a Traps Event Point
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        To add a trap, click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel, select
        <Bold>Traps</Bold> from the Event Point type list, and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>Edit EventPoint</Bold> window opens with the normal common properties, trigger
        settings, listening mode, and Traps-specific settings.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_add_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Common Properties
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Traps uses the standard Event Point common properties: index number, Event Point type, letter
        group, colour, position, facing direction, trigger settings, and listening mode.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The <Bold>position</Bold> controls where the trap appears. The <Bold>facing direction</Bold>
        is also important because the steam direction can be relative to the Event Point’s facing arrow.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_common_properties.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Position
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Use <Bold>Select Position on Map</Bold> to place the steam trap near the pipe, vent, wall,
        floor, or object where the steam should originate. For damaging traps, place it where the
        player or NPCs can actually pass through the steam’s range.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Facing Direction
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The steam’s direction can depend on the Event Point’s facing arrow. Select the Event Point
        in the viewport and rotate the orange facing handle if the steam needs to spray toward a
        specific direction.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_position_facing.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Required Listening Mode: Active While
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Steam traps are not a normal “fire once and remain true” event. They need to remain active
        while their trigger condition is active. For that reason, Steam Jet traps should use:
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Listening Mode:</Bold> Active While.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        This is the most important setup detail for Steam Jet traps. If the listening mode is set to
        <Bold>Active</Bold> instead, the trap may not behave correctly.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Do not skip this:</Run>
                <Run>
                    For Steam Jet traps, set Listening Mode to Active While. This is required for the trap to operate correctly.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_active_while.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Trap Type
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Trap Type</Bold> field determines which trap is created. Currently, the available
        option is <Bold>Steam Jet</Bold>.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_type.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Steam Jet</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Creates a jet of steam that sprays from the Event Point. The steam can be harmful to the
        player and enemies. It is most useful around pipes, vents, machinery, industrial walls, or
        environmental hazards.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Steam Direction
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Direction</Bold> property controls the direction the steam sprays relative to the
        Event Point’s facing direction arrow.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_direction.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Up</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The steam shoots straight upward into the air. Use this for floor vents, broken pipes, or
        rising steam effects.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Forward</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The steam shoots forward in the direction of the Event Point’s facing arrow. Use this for
        wall pipes, horizontal vents, or directional hazards.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Down</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        The steam shoots downward toward the ground. Use this for overhead pipes, ceiling vents, or
        downward pressure jets.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Facing tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    For Forward steam, rotate the Event Point’s orange facing handle so the arrow points in the direction the steam should spray.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Animation Parameters
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Steam Jet traps can be animated with a repeating on/off pattern. The animation parameters
        control how quickly steam escapes, how far it reaches, and which steps in the animation
        sequence are active.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_animation_parameters.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Speed
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Speed</Bold> controls how quickly the steam escapes or animates. Typical values are
        <Bold>1–10</Bold>. Lower values are slower or gentler. Higher values make the steam effect
        faster or more aggressive.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Steps
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Every frame of gameplay can be thought of as a <Bold>step</Bold>. The <Bold>Steps</Bold>
        value controls how many animation states exist in the trap’s repeating sequence.
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        For example, if Steps is set to <Bold>5</Bold>, the editor gives you five step states that
        can each be switched on or off. This lets you create a repeating steam pattern rather than a
        constant jet.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Range
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        <Bold>Range</Bold> controls how far the steam reaches in its relative direction. Typical
        values are <Bold>1–10</Bold>. A higher range means the steam reaches further.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Step Activation Pattern
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        The <Bold>Step Activation Pattern</Bold> controls which steps in the sequence are active.
        Each step has an on/off checkbox. This is how you create rhythmic steam bursts.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Image Source="pack://application:,,,/UrbanChaosMissionEditor;component/Help/Images/mission_traps_step_pattern.png"
               MaxWidth="720" Stretch="Uniform"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="18" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#9FE3A6" Margin="0,10,0,4">
        Example: Five-Step Pattern
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        If you set <Bold>Steps</Bold> to <Bold>5</Bold>, five checkboxes appear. To create this
        pattern:
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,6,0,8">
        <Border Background="#25272B" BorderBrush="#444" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="10">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#E0E0E0" FontFamily="Consolas">
on, off, off, on, off
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <List MarkerStyle="Disc" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Step 1:</Bold> checked / on.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Step 2:</Bold> unchecked / off.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Step 3:</Bold> unchecked / off.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Step 4:</Bold> checked / on.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph><Bold>Step 5:</Bold> unchecked / off.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <Paragraph Margin="0,6,0,0">
        The trap repeats that on/off sequence during gameplay.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Practical Uses
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Cosmetic Steam</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use Steam Jet traps to add life to industrial maps, factories, basements, pipes, sewers,
        or machinery areas. A low range and slow pattern can make the environment feel active
        without being too dangerous.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Environmental Hazard</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use stronger range and faster or more frequent activation to create a real hazard the player
        must avoid. Because steam can harm the player or enemies, test the placement carefully.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Timing Challenge</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Use a step pattern that alternates on and off so the player must time movement through the trap.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Hiding or Protecting Items</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        Steam traps can hide items from the player or make an item harder to reach. For example,
        a pickup may be visible behind a steam burst, requiring the player to wait for the safe
        moment or disable the trap first.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#E8B84B" Margin="8,8,0,1">Switch-Controlled Trap</Paragraph>
    <Paragraph Margin="24,0,0,0">
        A steam trap can be dynamically turned off through mission logic. For example, the player
        presses a switch, and that trigger kills or disables the trap.
    </Paragraph>

    <BlockUIContainer>
        <Border Height="1" Background="#444" Margin="0,14,0,12"/>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,0,0,4">
        Turning Steam Traps Off with Mission Logic
    </Paragraph>
    <Paragraph>
        Steam traps can be used as part of mission logic rather than only as static hazards. For
        example, a switch, dependency, or other trigger can turn the trap off.
    </Paragraph>

    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create a Steam Jet trap blocking or protecting an area.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trap to use <Bold>Listening Mode: Active While</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Create a switch or other trigger Event Point.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Use mission logic to kill, deactivate, or stop the trap when the switch is used.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Test that the trap stops and the player can safely pass or reach the item.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#2A2F3A" BorderBrush="#4A5A7A" BorderThickness="1"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="12">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#AFC8FF">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Design tip:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Steam traps are especially useful when the mission gives the player a problem first,
                    then provides a switch, dependency, or objective that disables the trap.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22" FontWeight="SemiBold" Foreground="#7AD7FF" Margin="0,12,0,4">
        Basic Steam Trap Workflow
    </Paragraph>
    <List MarkerStyle="Decimal" Margin="16,2,0,0">
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>Add</Bold> in the Event Points panel.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Select <Bold>Traps</Bold> and click <Bold>OK</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Place the Event Point where the steam should originate.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Rotate the Event Point facing arrow if using <Bold>Forward</Bold> direction.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Trap Type</Bold> to <Bold>Steam Jet</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Choose the steam direction: <Bold>Up</Bold>, <Bold>Forward</Bold>, or <Bold>Down</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Speed</Bold>, usually between <Bold>1–10</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Range</Bold>, usually between <Bold>1–10</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Steps</Bold> to define the length of the repeating activation sequence.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Tick or untick the step activation checkboxes to define the on/off pattern.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set <Bold>Listening Mode</Bold> to <Bold>Active While</Bold>.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Set the trigger condition that should make the trap active.</Paragraph></ListItem>
        <ListItem><Paragraph>Click <Bold>OK</Bold>, save, and test the trap in game.</Paragraph></ListItem>
    </List>

    <BlockUIContainer Margin="0,8,0,8">
        <Border Background="#4A2424" BorderBrush="#C45A5A" BorderThickness="2"
                CornerRadius="4" Padding="14">
            <TextBlock TextWrapping="Wrap" Foreground="#FFD0D0" FontSize="15">
                <Run FontWeight="Bold">Final checklist:</Run>
                <Run>
                    Steam Jet selected, direction set, range set, steps configured, step pattern checked, and Listening Mode set to Active While.
                    If the trap does not work, check Active While first.
                </Run>
            </TextBlock>
        </Border>
    </BlockUIContainer>

</FlowDocument>
